<font color="#FF0000">WHATS IT LIKE AT THE EDGE?</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 18 20:54:28 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc,<br><br>
Just a question.  Have you had one of those experiences in your life that creates the gift that keeps on giving?  I know it wouldn't be war, but I know that all experience does  not require war.<br><br>
I have wondered what the impact of listening to years of troubled minds has upon a shrink.  There must be a price to pay to carry all that baggage.  I have watched them come in to council all individuals when there is a violent death.  They question me briefly and say I don't need them.  Must know when the rig is dead.  I see others shattered from the experience.  I have a group on tap for trauma counciling when my team gets into the heavy stuff.<br><br>
Give us your views.  Do you hurt at night?  Do you get angry when someone burdens you with more than you were prepared for?  What is like when you lose a patient you thought you saved, but just checked out.<br><br>
It is not idle curiosity or a trick question.  I have seen men during an investigation suddenly realize that had caused  a death and watched them die before my eyes.  What does it take to bring them back.  I have wondered do you remove their guilt, if so how when they know or feel they are at fault.<br><br>
SW
